<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="29" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Rodríguez">Rodriguez</normalizedToken>
&amp; Campos 1816
</emphasis>
was described as having been collected in primary forest. The range in elevation that has been reported is 1800-3000 m (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Distribution map of Cuatrecasanthus species." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10127" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="29">
This species was the first member of the genus to be described. At the time of its description, a comparison was made to Brazilian species of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Eremanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Eremanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, members of the comparatively distantly related subtribe 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Lychnophorinae">Lychnophorinae</taxonomicName>
. Herbaria that might hold Jelski collections from Peru and therefore might have additional isolectotypes (according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Chaudhri, MN" journalOrPublisher="Regnum Vegetabile" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" pagination="1 - 473" refId="B1" refString="Chaudhri, MN, Vegter, IH, DeWal, CM, 1972. Index Herbariorum part II(3), Collectors I-L. Regnum Vegetabile 86: 1 - 473" title="Index Herbariorum part II (3), Collectors I-L." volume="86" year="1972">Chaudhri et al. 1972</bibRefCitation>
) are F, KRA, NY and W.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
